<ul class="accordion">
	<li>
	    <h2 class="head"><a href="#">Why TaskPaper?</a></h2>
	    <div class="content">
			<p>I created TaskPaper as an alternative to more complex task manager databases. I think that most people are better served by TaskPaper&#8217;s simpler solution.</p>

			<h3 id="works_like_a_text_editor">Works like a text editor</h3>

			<p>Type your lists into TaskPaper and each line is formatted into a project, task, or note. TaskPaper doesn’t force a particular system on you; it provides you with basic to-do list elements and then you use them as you see fit.</p>

			<h3 id="feels_like_a_magic_piece_of_paper">Feels like a magic piece of paper</h3>

			<p>TaskPaper has a magic trick. It understands your list's structure and will instantly filter your list to show only items of interest. TaskPaper’s filter system is simple to use—focus on a particular project or tag with a single tap. It also supports advanced searching if need.</p>

			<h3 id="stay_synced_between_work_home_and_your_iphone">Stay synced between work, home, and your iPhone</h3>

			<p>TaskPaper uses the <a href="http://www.simpletext.ws">SimpleText.ws</a> sync service to keep your lists synced. TaskPaper for iPhone has SimpleText sync built in. TaskPaper for Mac uses <a href="/products/simpletext">SimpleText for Mac</a> to stay synced.</p>

			<h3 id="other_options">Other options</h3>

			<ul>
			<li>Visit TaskPaper&#8217;s <a href="/wiki/TaskPaper">wiki</a> to learn about related projects.</li>
			<li>If TaskPaper isn&#8217;t for you then try out <a href="http://www.omnigroup.com/applications/omnifocus/">OmniFocus</a> or <a href="http://www.culturedcode.com/things/">Things</a> for a different approach.</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
	</li>
	<li>
	    <h2 class="head"><a href="#">What does it look like?</a></h2>
